On Isleme¶

  • Gri seviyedeki ekmek goruntusunde, gozeneklerin belirgin olmasi
    icin histogram germe islemi uygulanir.

  • Histogram germe islemi, histogrami genis bolgeye yayar. Bu sayede goruntulerin kontrasti iyilestirilmis olur. Histogram germe ile histogram esitleme farkliliklari olsada benzerdir.

  • Asagidaki goruntuye histogram esitleme uygulayalim ve sonuclari gorelim.

timg = cv.imread("test.png")
img = cv.cvtColor(timg, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)

hist = cv.calcHist([img], [0], None, [256], [0, 256])
axs[0, 0].imshow(img, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 1].plot(hist)

img2 = cv.equalizeHist(img)
hist2 = cv.calcHist([img2], [0], None, [256], [0, 256])
axs[1, 0].imshow(img2, cmap='gray')
axs[1, 1].plot(hist2)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.plot();

  • Ciktiya baktigimizda, ekmegin yuzeyi acik renk, ekmegin gozenekleri ise koyu renkte oldugu goruluyor.

  • Bu adim ile birlikte on isleme asamalari bitmis oluyor.

Goruntu Isleme¶

  • Bu kisimda islemeye hazir hale gelen goruntuler OTSU yontemiyle esiklenerek ikili goruntu haline donusturulecektir. Bu yontemler asagidaki diyagramda gosterilmistir.

  • OTSU, gri seviyede goruntu uzerinde uygulanan esik belirleme yontemidir. Bu yontem bir goruntudeki pikselleri farkli siniflara ayirir.
  • Bu ornekte, $M*N$ lik bir goruntunun arka plan ve on plan seklinde iki sinifa ayrildigi varsayilmaktadir.
  • Siniflar arasi varyans $J(t) = _0 + _1$ ile tanimlanir

  • Her bir sinifin varyansi ise asagidaki esitlikler ile tanimlanir.

    • $_0 = _0(\mu_0-\mu_t)^2$
    • $_1 = _1(\mu_1-\mu_t)^2$
      • $_i$ : Sinifin yogunlugu
      • $_i$ :Sinifin agirlik ortalamasi
      • $_t$: Goruntunun ortalamasi

  • Bu varyans degerlerini asagidaki esitlikler ile hesaplariz:

    • $_0, _0$ icin
      • $_0 = _\{i=0\}^\{t-1\} p_i$
      • $\mu_0 = _\{i=0\}^\{t-1\}p_iX(i)$
    • $_1, _1$ icin
      • $_1 = _\{i=t\}^\{mn-1\} p_i$
      • $\mu_1 = _\{i=t\}^\{mn-1\}p_iX(i)$

  • $p_i$, $i$ tonunun gelme olasiligidir

  • $X(i)$ $i.$ renk seviyesidir.

  • Goruntunun ortalamasi ise;

    • $_T = _\{i=0\}^\{mn-1\}p_iX(i)$

# https://scikit-image.org/docs/dev/auto_examples/applications/plot_human_mitosis.html

from scipy import ndimage as ndi
from skimage import (
    color, feature, filters, measure, segmentation
)

def crop(img, sl=5):
    img = img.copy()
    w, h = img.shape
    q1, q2 = w//sl, h//sl

    return img[q1:w-q1, q2:h-q2]

# Otsu Thresholding
def doOtsuThresholding(img, classes=2):
    th = filters.threshold_multiotsu(img, classes=classes)
    regions = np.invert(np.digitize(img, bins=th))

    return th, regions

# Cell Labeling
def doCellLabeling(img):
    cells = np.invert(img > th[0])
    labeled_cells = measure.label(cells)
    
    """ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance_transform
        On yuz piksellerin, arka yuz piksellerine olan uzakligini verir"""
    distance = ndi.distance_transform_edt(cells)
    local_max_coords = feature.peak_local_max(distance, min_distance=8)
    local_max_mask = np.zeros(distance.shape, dtype=bool)
    local_max_mask[tuple(local_max_coords.T)] = True
    markers = measure.label(local_max_mask)
    segmented_cells = segmentation.watershed(-distance, markers, mask=cells)
    color_labels = color.label2rgb(segmented_cells, img, alpha=0.9, bg_label=0)

    return cells, segmented_cells, color_labels

cimg = img2.copy() #crop(img2)
th, regions = doOtsuThresholding(cimg)
cells, segmented_cells, color_labels  = doCellLabeling(cimg)

# Outputs
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15, 15))

ax[0, 0].imshow(img2, cmap='gray')
ax[0, 0].set_title('Equalized Gray Image')

ax[0, 1].imshow(regions, cmap='gray')
ax[0, 1].set_title('Otsu Threshold')

ax[1, 0].imshow(cells, cmap='gray')
ax[1, 0].set_title('Cells')

ax[1, 1].imshow(color_labels, cmap='gray')
ax[1, 1].set_title('Segmented Cells')

ax[2, 0].imshow(img, cmap='gray')
ax[2, 0].set_title('Normal Image')

ax[2, 1].imshow(np.invert(img2), cmap='gray')
ax[2, 1].set_title('Inverted Equalized Image')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cv2 as cv

from skimage import data, feature, filters, measure, segmentation, color
from scipy import ndimage
from google.colab.patches import cv2_imshow as cim

coins = data.coins()

edges = np.uint8(filters.sobel(coins)*255)
markers = np.zeros_like(coins)
x, y = 1, 2
markers[coins < 30.] = y
markers[coins > 150.] = x

ws = segmentation.watershed(edges, markers)

seg1 = measure.label(ws == x)
colored = color.label2rgb(seg1, image=coins, bg_label=0)
plt.imshow(colored[..., ::-1]);

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cv2 as cv

from google.colab.patches import cv2_imshow as cim

coins = data.coins()
blured_img = cv.GaussianBlur(coins, ksize=(5, 5), sigmaX=0)
ret, thresh = cv.threshold(blured_img, 123, 255, cv.THRESH_TRUNC)
dilate = cv.dilate(thresh, kernel=(3, 3), iterations=5)
canny_img = np.uint8(feature.canny(thresh)*255)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15, 15))

ax[0, 0].imshow(coins, cmap='gray')
ax[0, 0].set_title("Original Image")

ax[0, 1].imshow(blured_img, cmap='gray')
ax[0, 1].set_title("Gaussian Blur")

ax[1, 0].imshow(thresh, cmap='gray')
ax[1, 0].set_title("Trunc Thresholding")

ax[1, 1].imshow(canny_img, cmap='gray')
ax[1, 1].set_title("Canny")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.plot()
